Baezy Bot Terms of Service

Effective Date: July 20, 2026
Bot Name: Baezy
Prefix: !
Current Version: Beta 0.7.0

1. Acceptance of Terms

By inviting, using, interacting with, or allowing Baezy to operate in a Discord server, you agree to these Terms of Service. These terms apply to all users, moderators, administrators, server owners, and communities where Baezy is present.

If you do not agree with these terms, you should not use Baezy and may remove the bot from your server.

2. About Baezy

Baezy is a custom Discord bot designed to provide community, moderation, utility, entertainment, reaction-role, and Twitch-related features.

Baezy may provide features including, but not limited to:

General bot and server information commands
Fun and community flavor commands
Moderation commands and moderation case logging
Deleted-message logging
Reaction role assignment
Automatic role assignment for new members
Twitch go-live notifications
Polls, embeds, color tools, and administrative posting tools
Bot status, changelog, and help documentation

Baezy is currently under active development and may change over time.

3. Eligibility

Baezy is intended for use within Discord servers and must be used in accordance with:

Discord’s Terms of Service
Discord’s Community Guidelines
The rules of any server where Baezy is used
Any applicable local, state, national, or international laws

Server owners and administrators are responsible for ensuring that Baezy is used appropriately within their communities.

4. Server Owner and Administrator Responsibility

By adding Baezy to a server, the server owner or authorized administrator confirms that they have permission to add bots and manage bot permissions within that server.

Server owners and administrators are responsible for:

Configuring Baezy’s permissions appropriately
Ensuring Baezy’s role is placed correctly in the Discord role hierarchy
Deciding which channels Baezy can access
Deciding which users may access moderation, administrator, or owner-level commands
Reviewing how Baezy’s logging features are used
Informing server members when moderation or message logging features are active, where appropriate

Baezy’s developer is not responsible for misuse caused by improper server configuration, excessive permissions, or unauthorized access granted by server staff.

5. User Conduct

Users may not use Baezy to:

Harass, threaten, abuse, or target other users
Evade server moderation
Spam commands, mentions, embeds, polls, or reactions
Attempt to crash, overload, exploit, or disrupt the bot
Use bot features to violate Discord’s Terms of Service
Use administrative tools, such as !speak or !embed, to impersonate others in a harmful or deceptive way
Abuse reaction roles, auto-roles, or role assignment features
Use Baezy for illegal, malicious, or harmful activity

Baezy may refuse to respond, fail safely, or be removed from servers where misuse occurs.

6. Command Access and Permissions

Some Baezy commands are available to all members, while others require Discord permissions or special access.

Examples include:

Moderation commands may require permissions such as Ban Members, Moderate Members, Manage Messages, or Manage Channels
Administrative commands may require Administrator
Restart and system-check commands may be restricted to approved user IDs
Reaction roles and auto-role features require Baezy to have Manage Roles
Twitch announcements may require permissions to mention roles or @everyone

Baezy follows Discord’s permission system where applicable, but server owners are responsible for ensuring that permissions are assigned safely.

7. Moderation Features

Baezy may include moderation tools such as:

User information lookup
Ban and unban commands
Timeout and untimeout commands
Message purge commands
Channel lock and unlock commands
Moderation case logging
Deleted-message logging

Moderation actions may be recorded in local bot data files, such as modlogs.json, depending on the feature used.

Baezy’s moderation tools are intended to assist server staff, but final responsibility for moderation decisions belongs to the server’s staff team.

Baezy does not determine whether a moderation action is fair, appropriate, or justified. It only performs actions requested by authorized users.

8. Deleted Message Logging

If enabled, Baezy may log deleted messages to a configured Discord channel.

Deleted-message logs may include:

The original message author
The channel where the message was deleted
The message ID
The deleted text content, if available
Attachment links, if available

Discord does not always provide bots with full information about deleted messages. Baezy may not be able to determine who deleted a message unless additional audit-log-based functionality is added.

Server owners and administrators are responsible for deciding whether deleted-message logging is appropriate for their community and for informing users where required.

9. Reaction Roles and Auto-Roles

Baezy may assign or remove roles based on:

A user joining the server
A user reacting to a configured reaction-role message
A user removing a reaction from a configured reaction-role message

Reaction-role systems may use standard Unicode emojis or custom Discord emoji IDs.

Baezy can only assign or remove roles that are below Baezy’s highest role in the Discord role hierarchy. If role assignment fails, server administrators are responsible for checking Baezy’s permissions and role placement.

10. Twitch Notifications

Baezy may check Twitch for configured streamers and post go-live notifications in configured Discord channels.

Twitch notification features may include:

Streamer name
Stream title
Game or category
Viewer count
Twitch stream link
Stream thumbnail
Role pings or @everyone mentions, depending on configuration

Baezy relies on Twitch API availability and correct Twitch application credentials. Twitch-related features may fail or be delayed if Twitch is unavailable, if credentials are invalid, or if the bot lacks permission to post in the configured Discord channel.

11. Entertainment and Randomized Commands

Baezy includes entertainment commands such as romance checks, vibe checks, joke commands, randomized reports, mock text, and other playful outputs.

These commands are intended for fun and should not be interpreted as factual, serious, personal, medical, psychological, legal, financial, or professional assessments.

Users and server staff are responsible for ensuring that entertainment commands are used in a respectful and appropriate way.

12. Data Collection and Storage

Baezy may process or temporarily access Discord data necessary to operate its features.

Depending on configuration and usage, Baezy may process or store:

Discord user IDs
Discord usernames or display names
Discord server IDs and names
Discord channel IDs and names
Role IDs
Message IDs
Moderation case information
Reasons provided for moderation actions
Deleted message content, if deleted-message logging is enabled
VIP or Member of the Day history
Restart confirmation data
Reaction-role configuration data
Twitch stream information received from Twitch’s API

Baezy does not require users to create accounts outside of Discord.

13. Data Persistence

Some Baezy data may be stored locally on the server hosting the bot.

Examples may include:

data/modlogs.json
data/vip_history.json
data/restart_notice.json
Bot configuration files
Runtime logs
System journal logs

Some data is temporary and may be deleted automatically, while other data may persist until manually removed by the bot owner or server administrator.

14. Data Sharing

Baezy does not sell user data.

Baezy may send data to third-party services only as needed for normal operation. For example:

Discord receives and processes bot commands, messages, reactions, role changes, and moderation actions
Twitch may be contacted to check whether configured streamers are live
The hosting provider may process server logs, runtime activity, or system metrics

Baezy’s developer or operator may review logs for troubleshooting, maintenance, abuse prevention, or debugging.

15. Data Removal

Server owners or authorized administrators may request removal of locally stored Baezy data where technically possible.

Some Discord-side data, such as sent messages, embeds, reactions, or audit logs, may need to be removed directly within Discord.

Some operational logs may remain temporarily in server logs or system journals until they expire or are manually cleared.

